<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>
  <strong>Notification</strong> is the runnable surface that realizes the
  <a href="/intents/feedback/">Feedback Intent</a> — a transient, non-blocking message that appears, is
  accessibly announced, persists for a bounded time (or until dismissed), and is removed. It captures the
  general UX particularities every notification shares — <em>temporary, non-blocking, dismissable, queued,
  severity-weighted, accessibly announced</em> — and leaves the <strong>presentation</strong> (a corner
  toast, a snackbar, a banner-position notice) to the implementation. The standard defines behaviour; the
  implementation picks the look.
</p>
<p>
  It is deliberately distinct from three neighbours: the OS-level
  <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/API/Notifications_API">Web Notifications API</a>
  (system notifications outside the tab, permission-gated — a separate capability under Web Permissions
  <a href="/backlog/009-gap-13-webpermissions-project/">#009</a>); <a href="/blocks/background-task-surface/">background-task-surface</a>
  (a <em>persistent</em> long-running-task surface); and inline <a href="/intents/message/">Message</a>
  banners (<em>structural</em>, in document flow). A notification is in-page, transient, and out-of-flow.
</p>

